cs.CR, cs.IT, cs.CC, cs.DS, cs.CE 

This paper deals with information-theoretic security in the context of secure computation protocols, which is a topic that falls under the scope of several computer science sub-categories. The most likely category is cs.CR (Cryptography and Security), as the paper focuses on secure computation protocols and their security properties. The second likely category is cs.IT (Information Theory), as the paper provides an information-theoretic characterization of unconditionally secure computation protocols. The third likely category is cs.CC (Computational Complexity), as secure computation protocols often involve complex algorithms and computational problems. The fourth likely category is cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), as the paper presents a protocol for Hamming distance computation. The fifth likely category is cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science), as secure computation protocols have applications in various fields, including finance and science.
